Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: Anthropology is a science of mutual surprise

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: Are there two ways of knowing the world—a submissive and a devouring way? They end up roughly the same place.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: What is the conversation of lovers? Compared with ordinary talk, it is as bread to stones.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: When is a pilgrim like a letter of the alphabet? When he cries out.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: How is a pilgrim like a blacksmith? He bends iron. Love bends him.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: At midnight, fireworks in the plaza. No photographs—you know what fireworks are like. Tawdry, staggering, irresistible, like human love.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: I took no maps, I cannot read maps—why press a seal on running water?

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: Enlightenment is not a place, no use rushing to get there.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: Wind does not stop by day here, does not stop by night, it keeps belling, boasting, wrestling, rinsing, disheveling, bonfiring, boistering down—the black morning tea blows out of the c

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: a man has locks all over his body. But women are numb or liars or never stop thinking, you can not make me stop thinking.

Title: Plainwater
Author: Anne Carson
HighlightText: Natural language is as brittle as pearl and the principle of noncontradiction too basic to be demonstrated, Aristotle avows, it can only be refuted. A single counterexample will do. Up, Daruma.
